pitches:
  30_second: {'duration': '30 seconds', 'target_audience': 'Anyone — networking events, quick introductions', 'pitch': "I'm Ganesh Giridhar, a second-year Computer Science student at Amrita Vishwa Vidyapeetham. I build systems that solve real problems — my flagship project automates my family's rice distribution business with an offline-first mobile app. I've competed in AI hackathons at IIT Madras and IIT Kharagpur, interned as a full-stack developer at CodSoft, and designed a water purification system for a rural village through field research. I think in architectures, not just code.", 'key_hooks': ['Family business automation — real users, real stakes', 'Hackathons at IIT Madras and IIT Kharagpur', 'Systems thinker, not just a coder']}
  2_minute: {'duration': '2 minutes', 'target_audience': 'Recruiters, mentors, potential collaborators', 'pitch': "I'm Ganesh Giridhar, a B.Tech CSE student at Amrita Vishwa Vidyapeetham, Coimbatore, graduating in 2028 with a current CGPA of 8.36. I come from Visakhapatnam, where I scored 96.17% in my SSC and 96.5% in Intermediate exams before diving into engineering.

What defines me isn't just academics — it's what I build. My most important project is RiceAgent Pro, a Flutter-based offline-first app that automates my father's rice distribution business. Real inventory management, GST billing, WhatsApp integration — built for users who actually depend on it daily.

On the AI side, I built ExecuCode during the Meta PyTorch OpenEnv Challenge — an AI-powered code grading platform using FastAPI, Gemini API, and Docker with autonomous agent loops. I've also built a real-time RAG pipeline using Pathway AI with PostgreSQL and Kafka integration.

I've competed at IIT Madras's Shaastra AI hackathon, IIT Kharagpur's Data Hack, the HDFC FinCal Hackathon, and the Gemini 3 Hackathon. During my CodSoft internship, I shipped two full MERN-stack applications — an e-commerce platform and a project management tool.

Beyond code, I spent time in Ramanathapuram through Amrita's Live-in-Labs program, designing a multi-stage water purification system for a village using Human-Centered Design. That experience taught me that the best engineering serves people who can't ask for it.

I operate on what I call a linear paradigm — no waiting for dramatic turning points, just consistent, compounding effort with architectural clarity.", 'key_sections': ['Academic foundation and credibility', 'Flagship project with real-world impact', 'AI and systems engineering depth', 'Hackathon and competitive experience', 'Internship delivery', 'Research with social impact', 'Personal philosophy']}
  technical_audience: {'duration': '60–90 seconds', 'target_audience': 'Engineers, developers, technical interviewers', 'pitch': "I'm Ganesh — I work across the full stack but my strongest instinct is systems architecture. My most complex project is RiceAgent Pro, an offline-first Flutter app using Riverpod for state management and Drift (SQLite) for local persistence, with a sync architecture designed for unreliable connectivity in field conditions.

I built ExecuCode — an AI code grading engine with FastAPI, Gemini API agents in autonomous evaluation loops, and Docker-based sandboxed execution. The architecture uses AST analysis for deterministic grading combined with LLM-powered qualitative feedback.

For the Gemini 3 Hackathon, I built a RAG pipeline using Pathway AI with live document indexing, hybrid vector search, and Kafka-PostgreSQL synchronization. I also shipped FLIP WARS — a JavaFX strategic game with Minimax, alpha-beta pruning, dynamic programming, and Zobrist hashing for state optimization.

My stack spans Python, Java, JavaScript/TypeScript, Flutter/Dart, React, Next.js, Node.js, FastAPI, PostgreSQL, MySQL, Docker, Firebase, and various AI frameworks including LangChain and Gemini API. I think in data flows and system boundaries.", 'technical_highlights': ['Offline-first sync architecture (Riverpod + Drift)', 'Autonomous AI agent loops with sandboxed execution', 'RAG pipeline with live indexing and hybrid search', 'Game AI with Minimax, alpha-beta pruning, Zobrist hashing', 'Full-stack MERN delivery under internship constraints']}
  casual_introduction: {'duration': '20–30 seconds', 'target_audience': 'Peers, social settings, campus events', 'pitch': "Hey, I'm Ganesh — from Vizag, studying CS here at Amrita in Coimbatore. I build apps and AI stuff. My coolest project is probably an app I made for my dad's rice business — it handles everything from inventory to GST bills, and it works offline because the warehouse doesn't always have great signal. I've done a couple of hackathons at IIT Madras and Kharagpur, and I spent some time in a village near Ramanathapuram designing a water filter system for the community. When I'm not coding, you'll find me obsessing over cyberpunk UI design or figuring out how to automate something that shouldn't take as long as it does.", 'personality_notes': ['Genuine and approachable without being self-deprecating', 'Leads with relatable stories, not credentials', 'Subtle flex through specificity rather than bragging', 'Shows breadth of interests beyond just tech']}

{
  "id": "behavioral_001",
  "question": "Tell me about yourself.",
  "star_answer": {
    "situation": "I am a B.Tech Computer Science and Engineering student at Amrita Vishwa Vidyapeetham, Coimbatore, graduating in 2028. I have a current CGPA of 8.36/10.",
    "task": "My goal has always been to build real-world systems, rather than just solving isolated toy coding problems.",
    "action": "I have spent my time building production-grade projects. My flagship project is RiceAgent Pro, an offline-first Flutter application using Riverpod and Drift (SQLite) that automates my family's rice distribution business in Andhra Pradesh. On the AI side, I built ExecuCode, an AI code-grading platform using FastAPI, Gemini API, and Docker to execute code in secure sandboxes. I've also interned at CodSoft, shipping two MERN-stack applications, and conducted field research in a rural village through Amrita's Live-in-Labs program to design a community water purification system.",
    "result": "These experiences have given me strong skills in Python, Java, JavaScript, Flutter, React, FastAPI, Node.js, and SQL, along with a deep appreciation for systems architecture.",
    "learning": "I operate on a 'linear paradigm'\u2014consistent, daily execution and clear design thinking are what build reliable, high-impact systems."
  }
}

{
  "id": "behavioral_002",
  "question": "Tell me about a challenging project you worked on.",
  "star_answer": {
    "situation": "I wanted to automate my family's rice distribution operations, which were slow, paper-heavy, and prone to transaction discrepancies. However, the warehouses and rural delivery locations often had extremely poor or non-existent cellular connectivity.",
    "task": "I had to design a business automation system, RiceAgent Pro, that allowed operators to manage orders, track inventory, and generate GST bills completely offline, then sync with a main server when a connection became available.",
    "action": "I chose Flutter and Dart for the cross-platform frontend. I integrated Drift as a SQLite ORM to handle local persistence. I designed a local-first sync architecture where the local database acts as the single source of truth. Offline changes are stored in a queue with transaction numbers, and I wrote conflict resolution logic on the server to merge data cleanly. I also implemented an Excel-import parser to ingest legacy wholesale records.",
    "result": "The app runs completely offline, allowing seamless invoice generation. It reduced order-to-billing time in our family business from days to minutes, processing real transaction records with zero sync data loss.",
    "learning": "This project taught me that user context dictates system requirements. An elegant cloud-only architecture is a failure if the user is standing in a metal warehouse with no network signal."
  }
}

{
  "id": "behavioral_003",
  "question": "Tell me about a time you failed.",
  "star_answer": {
    "situation": "During my preparation at Tirumala IIT & JEE Academy, I dedicated two years of intensive study to qualifying for the JEE Advanced and securing a seat at a top-tier IIT.",
    "task": "I needed to perform at an elite level on a highly competitive, multi-subject national exam.",
    "action": "I studied 12+ hours a day, solved thousands of complex mock problems, and maintained extreme discipline. Although I performed well in my board exams (96.5%) and qualified for JEE Mains, I did not qualify for JEE Advanced.",
    "result": "I did not get into an IIT and joined Amrita Vishwa Vidyapeetham instead.",
    "learning": "I learned to reframe failure as a learning architecture. The process taught me first-principles thinking and built resilience. I realized that my value as an engineer isn't defined by an institution's brand, but by the code I write and the systems I build."
  }
}

{
  "id": "behavioral_004",
  "question": "How do you handle pressure and tight deadlines?",
  "star_answer": {
    "situation": "During the Synaptix Frontier AI Hack at IIT Madras, our team had only 36 hours to build an AI prototype. Mid-way through the hackathon, we realized our initial approach to the LLM orchestration loop was too slow and hitting rate limits.",
    "task": "We had to quickly refactor the core AI logic to execute under time constraints, without sacrificing performance or presentation quality.",
    "action": "Instead of panicking, I structured our remaining time using a priority matrix. I immediately stripped out non-essential visual elements and focused on the core API pipeline. I implemented asynchronous requests in Python and introduced a local caching layer for common queries to avoid rate limits.",
    "result": "We completed the functional prototype with 3 hours to spare, presenting a working, real-time AI system that successfully handled evaluator test cases.",
    "learning": "Under pressure, speed is nothing without structural clarity. You must break down the problem, strip away the noise, and execute the minimal functional unit first."
  }
}

{
  "id": "behavioral_005",
  "question": "Describe a time you worked in a team.",
  "star_answer": {
    "situation": "During Amrita's Live-in-Labs program, I worked with a multidisciplinary team of students in Nediamanickam village, Ramanathapuram, to solve local water quality issues.",
    "task": "We had to design a community water purification system that was technically sound, cost-effective, and accepted by the rural residents.",
    "action": "Some team members wanted to use solar-powered filtration units because they sounded modern. I conducted field interviews using Participatory Rural Appraisal (PRA) and analyzed local resources. I pointed out that the village lacked the technical expertise to maintain solar panels, and dust would quickly degrade them. I advocated for a simpler, multi-stage gravity-fed sand and carbon filter system that the community could maintain themselves.",
    "result": "The team aligned around this practical design. We delivered a working model that the village elders could operate with minimal training.",
    "learning": "Teamwork is about listening to the user and setting aside engineering ego. The most advanced technical solution is useless if the community cannot maintain it."
  }
}

{
  "id": "behavioral_006",
  "question": "How do you learn new technologies?",
  "star_answer": {
    "situation": "I needed to build a real-time data streaming and document search pipeline for a project, but I had never used Pathway AI, Kafka, or vector databases before.",
    "task": "I had to learn these tools from scratch and implement a functioning pipeline within two weeks.",
    "action": "I started by reading the official documentation to understand the architectural lifecycle of Pathway's streaming engine. Rather than following generic video tutorials, I built a minimal prototype: a simple Python script that ingested a local file, computed embeddings, and stored them. Once I understood the basic data flow, I incrementally added Kafka for message streaming and PostgreSQL for persistence.",
    "result": "I successfully built the Pathway RAG Pipeline, showing how live document updates can be indexed and queried in real-time.",
    "learning": "The best way to learn is by building a skeleton. Read the core documentation, build a tiny working prototype to understand the abstractions, and then scale the complexity."
  }
}

{
  "id": "behavioral_007",
  "question": "Tell me about a time you solved a complex technical problem.",
  "star_answer": {
    "situation": "In FLIP WARS, a strategic tile-flipping game I built in Java, the AI opponent was extremely slow. It took over 10 seconds to make a move because the state space grew exponentially with every turn.",
    "task": "I had to optimize the AI engine to make decisions in under 1 second while maintaining high-quality strategic choices.",
    "action": "I implemented a Minimax algorithm with Alpha-Beta pruning to discard branches that didn't need evaluation. To optimize state lookups, I implemented Zobrist Hashing to memoize previously evaluated game states. I also wrote a custom graph-clustering algorithm using DFS to quickly calculate board regions.",
    "result": "The average turn calculation time dropped from 10+ seconds to less than 200 milliseconds, allowing smooth, real-time gameplay with a highly competitive AI.",
    "learning": "Complex problems require optimization at the algorithm and state level, not just throwing more hardware at the problem."
  }
}

{
  "id": "behavioral_008",
  "question": "Describe a leadership experience.",
  "star_answer": {
    "situation": "As the Unlox Campus Ambassador at Amrita University, I was responsible for driving student engagement and organizing workshops on technical skills.",
    "task": "I had to organize a workshop on web development and API integration for students who had varying levels of programming experience.",
    "action": "I designed the curriculum around building a real project\u2014a weather app\u2014rather than lecturing on syntax. I paired students with more coding experience with beginners. I also set up a GitHub repository with template branches so that students who fell behind could jump to a working checkpoint.",
    "result": "Over 50 students attended, and every single participant successfully built and deployed a working web application by the end of the session.",
    "learning": "Leadership is about creating the infrastructure for others to succeed. Clear organization, templates, and peer-matching build far more competence than loud charisma."
  }
}

{
  "id": "behavioral_009",
  "question": "How do you handle disagreements within a team?",
  "star_answer": {
    "situation": "During a hackathon project, my teammate and I disagreed on whether to use Firebase or PostgreSQL for a collaborative real-time editor.",
    "task": "We had to resolve the technical disagreement quickly to avoid wasting valuable hacking time.",
    "action": "Instead of arguing, I proposed a quick benchmarking exercise. I set up a simple script to test real-time write latencies and ease of data sync in both databases. We found that while PostgreSQL was better for structured querying, Firebase's out-of-the-box listener sockets saved us hours of boilerplate code for real-time synchronization under the 36-hour deadline.",
    "result": "We agreed to use Firebase for the hackathon MVP, which allowed us to ship a fully functional, collaborative editor on time.",
    "learning": "Disagreements should be resolved with data and context. Frame the decision around constraints like time, requirements, and user needs, rather than personal preferences."
  }
}

